  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An international organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- Develops recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides guidance and support for anti-money laundering efforts\n\n4. Basel Committee Principles\n- Offers banking supervision standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units that share information\n\nMany countries have also implemented their own national anti-money laundering (AML) laws, such as:\n- The United States Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- UK's Proceeds of Crime Act\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese international and national frameworks work together to detect and prevent money laundering globally.",
